@NODE INTRO "Introducing the SFMV Script File Generator"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Script File Generator@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

This is a simple program to enable you, the user, to create script files for
the  @{"SFMV  Player" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV_Player.Guide/MAIN}.  The  program  impliments a standard GUI (Graphical User
Interface),  allowing  you  to chose the files to be displayed by the player
and then saving the file out in the correct format.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADSAVE "Loading and saving script files"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Script File Generator@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

The  @{FG SHINE}'Load'@{FG TEXT}  and @{FG SHINE}'Save'@{FG TEXT} gadgets allow you to load and save SFMV Script Files
(Surprisingly enough!).  They will open up a standard ASL file requester and
let you select a script file for loading or saving.

The SFMV Script File is a simple ASCII file that can also be edited within a
text editor.

The default script path can be set using the SCRIPTPATH @{"Tooltype" LINK TOOLTYPES}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MUSIC "Music file selection"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Script File Generator@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

A  music  file  can  be  selected  using an ASL file requester.  Your chosen
module  will  then  be  played back during the execution of the SFMV Script.
The music file must be a P61A file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE OPTIONS "SFMV Script Playback Options"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Script File Generator@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}
The SFMV Script Generator allows you to set the various SFMV Player options,
these are:

@{fg highlight}@{u}Multi-Load@{uu}@{fg text}
This  option  specifies  whether  or not the SFMV Player should load all the
files  in  the  playlist  before  playback or to load each file when needed.
Multi-Load  option  should be enabled for large Hard disk based scripts, and
disabled for short floppy disk based versions.

@{fg highlight}@{u}Script Loop@{uu}@{fg text}
Enable  this  option  if  you  want  the  script  to loop after playback has
completed.

@{fg highlight}@{u}Display Mode@{uu}@{fg text}
The  display mode can be either PAL or NTSC and selects the default playback
mode  for  the  entire Script file.  Playing back animations in NTSC mode is
slightly  quick,  however it limits the display to 100 pixels high (PAL mode
is  128  pixels  high).   If  an  animation is greater than a 100 pixels and
displayed  in  NTSC  mode,  you'll  find the display doesn't fit the screen.
Also  bare  in  mind  that  not  all PAL televisions/monitors are capable to
display a NTSC screen.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PLAYLIST "The SFMV Script Playlist"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
 \_____ ~\  |'   __)/  \ /  \   X   /       @{fg text}Script File Generator@{fg shine}
 //       \ |     \/    Y    \     /
/_______  / \___  /\____|__  /\___/
~       \/      \/         \/@{fg text}
@{u}                                                                           @{uu}

The  Playlist  displays  the  list of files to be played by the SFMV Player.
Each  file can either be an IFF file to display or an SFMV file to playback.
The Script Generator will attempt to identify each file in the list.

The  list  consists of two columns.  The first contains the programs attempt
at  identifying  the file and the second column contains the actual filename
(right justified).

These are the code words used in column one.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}SFMV@{FG TEXT}	- A Shoah Full Motion Video file.
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}IFF@{FG TEXT}	- An IFF ILBM file.
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}STC@{FG TEXT}	- A  StoneCracked (compacted)  file,  the contents of which have not
          been checked.
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}UNKN@{FG TEXT}	- An  unknown  filetype,  this  file  is  unlikely  to work with the
          player!
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}EROR@{FG TEXT}	- A file error occurred, file not found, file is empty, etc.

The  first  three filetypes (SFMV, IFF and STC) are the normal filetypes you
would find in a player script.  The other two are likley to crash the player
or cause an error.

However  this  program  allows  you to include these files in a script.  For
example you may compact the SFMV files using a different compression program
to  Stonecracker  and then make use of a system patch to allow the player to
decrunch the files.  These files would be displayed as unknown in the Script
Generator.   Also  you  may load a script file which contains file pathnames
that  do  not  (or  no  longer)  exist(s)  on your system and these would be
displayed as errors.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ADD "Adding an item to the Playlist"
@{fg shine}  _____________________________   ____      @{FG FILL}@{"Main SFMV Guide" LINK SFMV:Guides/SFMV.Guide/MAIN}@{FG SHINE}
 /'  _____/\_   _____/'    \`  \ /'  /
